      "post_content": "It would have been great in EDH *except* that it contains those blue and black mana symbols in the text box. Red and white are really starved for solid repeatable draw effects, and Bloodletter Quill's relatively cheap casting and activation costs would make it a much more appealing alternative to many artifacts that make you feel kinda bad for using them ([Jayemdae Tome](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Jayemdae Tome), [Candles of Leng](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Candles of Leng), [Book of Rass](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Book of Rass), [Tower of Fortunes](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Tower of Fortunes), ect). These cards show up in decks from time to time, but I'm sure they'd be replaced with Bloodletter Quill if they were able to do so.\n  \n   \nBut blue and black are not so limited in there card advantage engines, and never need to bother with the dregs of the artifact tomes. Why would a blue & black deck ever play the Quill over [Necropotence](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Necropotence) or [Phyrexian Arena](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Phyrexian Arena)? Limiting the card to colors with better alternatives killed it. ",
      "posted_by": "scumbling1",
      "html": "<div class=\"post evenItem\" id=\"PopularPost164037\" style=\"background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">\n<span class=\"postContent\" id=\"ctl00_ctl00_ctl00_MainContent_SubContent_SubContent_popularPosts_postsRepeater_ctl08_post\">It would have been great in EDH <i>except</i> that it contains those blue and black mana symbols in the text box. Red and white are really starved for solid repeatable draw effects, and Bloodletter Quill's relatively cheap casting and activation costs  would make it a much more appealing alternative to many artifacts that make you feel kinda bad for using them (<a class=\"autoCard\" data:cardname=\"Jayemdae Tome\" href=\"/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Jayemdae Tome\">Jayemdae Tome</a>, <a class=\"autoCard\" data:cardname=\"Candles of Leng\" href=\"/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Candles of Leng\">Candles of Leng</a>, <a class=\"autoCard\" data:cardname=\"Book of Rass\" href=\"/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Book of Rass\">Book of Rass</a>, <a class=\"autoCard\" data:cardname=\"Tower of Fortunes\" href=\"/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Tower of Fortunes\">Tower of Fortunes</a>, ect). These cards show up in decks from time to time, but I'm sure they'd be replaced with Bloodletter Quill if they were able to do so.\r<br/> <br/>But blue and black are not so limited in there card advantage engines, and never need to bother with the dregs of the artifact tomes. Why would a blue &amp; black deck ever play the Quill over <a class=\"autoCard\" data:cardname=\"Necropotence\" href=\"/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Necropotence\">Necropotence</a> or <a class=\"autoCard\" data:cardname=\"Phyrexian Arena\" href=\"/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Phyrexian Arena\">Phyrexian Arena</a>? Limiting the card to colors with better alternatives killed it. </span>\n<div class=\"postDetails\" id=\"ctl00_ctl00_ctl00_MainContent_SubContent_SubContent_popularPosts_postsRepeater_ctl08_postDetails\" style=\"padding-top: 5px;\">\n<div class=\"reportAbuse\">\n<a href